A lot of people compared it to Love and Other Words, and I can definitely see the similarity, but this book was so much better.I loved the plot and the way the flashbacks were interwoven. I enjoyed reading both in present time and in the past. I love the way that the romance was built up over the years. It was so cute. I love Sam and (view spoiler)[I think that he deserves better than Percy (sorry). This would have been a 5 star read if it weren't for the plot twist, which I saw coming a mile away, but was still unexpected? I feel like it made no sense to the story and was a bit unoriginal but... it's still interesting drama, I guess.  (hide spoiler)]I wish we got more of Sue and Percy's parents in the book! This book really reminded me of The Summer I Turned Pretty but a much more mature and detailed version. I also loved Delilah's and Percy's friendship. It was super cute and had so much growth and development. To top this  off, I will say one more time, I LOVE SAM! He was such a cute love interest. I definitely recommend this book and will be reading more from this author....more

You don’t have to hide them.”I am so sad that I finished this book. I thoroughly enjoyed every second of it. This book is like a combination of A Little Life and Conversations with Friends, two of my all-time favorite books. I first discovered this book on Instagram and read the sample for it while trying to decide which books to bring with me on vacation. I really wanted to keep reading, so I bought it (best decision). This book is fairly new and so underrated. If you see this  and you love any Sally Rooney book or A Little Life, then stop everything you are doing and buy this book right now. Each chapter focused on a different character, and I loved reading about every single character. There wasn't a single character that I wasn't bored of while reading this. However, my favorite chapters were probably Eleanor's and Zoe's. This book made me laugh out loud and almost cry several times. The writing was impactful while also interesting and humorous. I have been so busy these past couple of months, but I have finally found some time to read.This book was a pleasant surprise. I picked it up on a whim, and I ended up really enjoying the story. I thought that the writing was decent and that the characters were developed and well thought out. Ivy was a really interesting character and I really enjoyed reading from her point of view. The side characters were also interesting to read and learn about. I thought all the characters added to the story, which made it really interesting. The plot was interesting, although I think it dragged a bit at some points. I think it could have been more interesting if there were more plot twists throughout the story because I felt like I was just reading about events that were leading up to the inevitable. review: 3.5 Stars “I am what I am. To look for reasons is beside the point.” Play It As It Lays is a very eccentric book and unlike anything I have ever read.3.5 Stars “I am what I am. To look for reasons is beside the point.” Play It As It Lays is a very eccentric book and unlike anything I have ever read. The writing in this is phenomenal - I felt like I understood the premise of the story even though I wasn't really sure of what exactly was going on in the plot and who the characters were. I really understood what was going on in Maria's head and Didion did a good job of detailing what its really like to feel like you're losing your mind. It's like she was able to write out emotions that I know I have felt before but was never able to articulate in the same way that Didion did in this book.Although I thought the writing was phenomenal, I had a hard time following the plot and understanding other characters' relationships to Maria, so it made it less of an enjoyable read for me. However, I am glad I read it, and look forward to reading more by Joan Didion in the future because of her writing style. I recommend if you're looking for something different!rip joan didion<3 ...more

review: 4.5 Stars“I want you always to remember me. Will you remember that I existed, and that I stood next to you here like this?”Wow.. this is definitely on4.5 Stars“I want you always to remember me. Will you remember that I existed, and that I stood next to you here like this?”Wow.. this is definitely one of those books that will stay with me for the rest of my life. The writing in this was absolutely phenomenal and the characters were so complex. The way that Murakami portrayed grieving in this book through his prose really got through to me, and especially towards the end of the book, I felt like I was right there, grieving with Toru.  I was always hungry for love. Just once, I wanted to know what it was like to get my fill of it – to be fed so much love I couldn't take any more. This book reminded me a bit of Sally Rooney's work (if it was written from the pov of a perverted man maybe?? lol) and even though nothing really happened in the book, I was always so immersed in it and I wanted to keep reading. When Toru was looking back on his memories with Naoko, I felt like I was looking back with him which really added to the book for me because it gave me a glimpse into exactly how he was feeling. I also loved Midori and I thought she was so relatable in a couple of ways. “I've had enough hurt already in my life. More than enough. Now I want to be happy.”The one thing about this book that REALLY bothered me was the way that the women were written. I saw a couple of s before reading the book about it, but I wanted to see for myself. I definitely agree that the way women were portrayed in this book was a bit problematic, especially some scenes in the book (and i did not like any of the vulgar sex scenes. they were awkward and i guess i just hated reading it from a mans pov). It would be a 5 star favorite if it wasn't for that, but I can't really look past them since they were such a prominent part of the story. review: 4.5 Stars“If God wanted me to give you up, he wouldn't have made me who I am.”ALEXA PLAY NOTHING NEW BY TAYLOR SWIFT!!First read of 2022!! So happ4.5 Stars“If God wanted me to give you up, he wouldn't have made me who I am.”ALEXA PLAY NOTHING NEW BY TAYLOR SWIFT!!First read of 2022!! So happy it was this one. As I'm writing this , I'm debating on the rating (might change it??). Because this is Sally Rooney, I feel inclined to give it 5 stars because I am so obsessed with her writing. However, I feel like this book is my least favorite out of the two I've read by her (though they are tough competition to beat bcs I absolutely ADORE them). The sole reason is probably the lack of plot in this one (in comparison to the other two). The other two barely had plot in them either but I feel like this one had even less. This book is definitely more mature than the other two and I enjoyed all the pretentiousness in Alice and Eileen's email exchanges. I thought it was very interesting to read about. The writing in this was beautiful as always. So many beautiful quotes that I have annotated. I think it's really fascinating that Rooney tried to embody herself through Alice's character. I really loved Elieen and I related to her so much. She is probably my favorite Sally Rooney character!! Like how is this woman my literal clone?? How are we thinking the same specific thoughts?? I loved her relationship with Simon so much and I'm happy with how it turned out. I thought Alice's and Felix's relationship was interesting but I liked it and I think it worked well for both of their characters. I love that this is the book I finished in 2022 because I feel like it really sets the tone for the year and my mindset about it: how beautiful life is no matter what is happening because of the people around you that you love and just the fact that you have the ability to just love and care about them no matter what. I think that it is so beautiful. Highly recommend this book (especially if you liked Rooney's last two books)....more

review: 3.75 Stars“Poor girls. The world fattens them on the promise of love. How badly they need it, and how little most of them will ever get.”This book was3.75 Stars“Poor girls. The world fattens them on the promise of love. How badly they need it, and how little most of them will ever get.”This book was very eerie, and disgusting at times, but intriguing. I do not know much about the Manson murders, but I wanted to learn more, and this gave me a little insight into what really happened. I really liked the way that this was written. There were many beautiful lines that contemplated girlhood and coming of age that I loved. There were many interesting points in the plot and I liked reading about the contrast with how Evie's home life was evolving vs her life at the ranch. I thought that Evie's attachment to Suzanna was intriguing as well. Although the plot was fast-paced and exciting, I felt as if it quickened very abruptly and that it would have made more sense if the author delved deeper into the characters, more specifically Suzanna and the other girls. I feel like it would have given the story dimension. I wish we learned more about the motives and how the cult really started, instead of the muddled explanation that we were given. I also would have loved to learn more about Evie's family, more specifically her grandmother and her mother. I feel like this could have created some crucial turning points in Evie's character. Overall, I would definitely recommend this book. It is super interesting and fast-paced. The prose is also great. I will be reading more of the author's books....more

review: 5 Stars"And there in the dark, he asks if it was really worth it.Were the instants of joy worth the stretches of sorrow?Were the moments of beauty wor5 Stars"And there in the dark, he asks if it was really worth it.Were the instants of joy worth the stretches of sorrow?Were the moments of beauty worth the year of pain?And she turns her head, and looks at him, and says 'Always.'"Finishing this book, I have no words. This was truly incredible, a literal masterpiece. The writing is absolutely beautiful and the way that the plot conveys the message of the story is absolutely immaculate.Addie LaRue makes a Faustian bargain with a devil to become immortal, but at the cost of being forgotten by everyone she meets. She is erased from the lives of her family and friends, but free of the constraints that they bound her to. She is able to travel the world and live the way she had always wished to. “Don't you remember, she told him then, when you were nothing but shadow and smoke?Darling, he'd said in his soft, rich way, I was the night itself.”The writing of this book was certainly amazing. Every chapter had a purpose and at least one memorable quote. This book showed how grief, joy, happiness, anger, jealousy, sorrow, love, and so many more emotions are all apart of living a fulfilled life. It showed that life is perfect because it is not perfect. That the moments of sorrow just make the moments of joy even better. All she knows is that she is tired, and he is the place she wants to rest. And that, somehow, she was happy. But it is not love.The different romantical aspects of this book were done so well. With Addie being able to experience a kind of love she never got to have, but also coming back to the comfort of the love that she had always had. The build-up between Addie's relationship with (view spoiler)[Luc (hide spoiler)] was so well done. I thought that their relationship was so well written and intricate. Her relationship with (view spoiler)[Henry (hide spoiler)] was bittersweet, but I loved it as well. Not as angsty, but refreshing, and the kind of love she deserved after all those years.As I mentioned before, I feel like the magical aspect of this book helped convey the message of the story even better. The fact that Addie made a deal with a devil to live forever, shows that even though she saw many great places and did live a fulfilling life, the one thing she wanted to be was remembered. (view spoiler)[Through Henry's deal, I was able to see how love's imperfections make it real. I will definitely remember when he was sitting with Bea, and she told him that you can't make someone love you. To be real, it has to be a choice that you make. (hide spoiler)]I definitely recommend this book!! This book may not be for everyone, but it is just the kind of book that I find to be perfect. I loved Schwab's writing style and it reminded me of Ava Lavender. I can't wait to read more of Schwab's work in the future and come back to re-read this....more

review: 3 Stars"I'm telling you, Eady, wars and treaties and even countries will all come and go. But your life is yours, singular and sacred, and you should 3 Stars"I'm telling you, Eady, wars and treaties and even countries will all come and go. But your life is yours, singular and sacred, and you should be with the person who makes it feel that way every blessed second you live it"Even though this series wasn't my favorite, I am sad it has come to an end. Although the books aren't the best, they are comfortable to read because they are so predictable and simple.I know this is an unpopular opinion, but I feel as if I enjoyed these last two books a bit more than the first three. I liked Eadlyn far more than America, because I feel like she actually grew throughout the book and was worried about many more things than just finding love, which made her much more complex. The way a book is written usually isn't a problem for me, but I feel like the author was a bit in over her head on this one. She used so many strange similes that sometimes I just cringed. The writing is simple and fairly easy to understand, but some things just had me thinking, 'Why?'.I was also happy to see more stuff going around in the world instead of the book just being centered around the romance. It made the plot a bit better and it was more interesting to read about all the different dynamics in their country, especially showing how even though they got rid of the castes, that wasn't the sole solution to fixing all the problems in their country.Although I feel the romance was a bit underdeveloped and the person she ended up with isn't exactly the person that I wanted her to end up with, it was still less predictable than who America ended up with, which I appreciated. However, in terms of romance, I liked America and Maxon's relationship more than who Eadlyn ended up with because I feel like the person Eadlyn ended up with was a bit random. Maxon and America were so cute in this book though!!Overall, this series isn't anything mind-blowing and amazing, its pretty mediocre. However, its a comfortable read and if you're looking to destress, I would certainly recommend this book because it is simple, safe, and predictable....more

Yes, she tried to stop it, but when a couple guards came for her, she just immediately gave up and started thinking about her love life instead. Also, when America found out what her country was truly built on, instead of finding a way to fix it and make it be known, she used it as a way to get back at Maxon , while also breaking his trust, for being with other girls - even though essentially what she was in was a BACHELORETTE where the BACHELOR has to choose between different women. If she couldn't choose him, then why did he have to wait around for her?  (hide spoiler)] This book is classified as being a dystopia/utopia, yet the only thing that the main character can think about is romance. However, I do feel like Maxon definitely had more to his character this, but The only reason I am 'Team Maxon' over 'Team Aspen' is because I think he is a more interesting character than Aspen, who is just a super flat character. Some positives to this book was that the world building was a bit better this time. I feel like I understand more of the history behind the world than I did in the previous book and I think that was definitely an interesting part. I think this book ended in a better way than the previous book as well, but it was still kind of a stupid ending. review: 5 Stars“You do not know how fast you have been running, how hard you have been working, how truly exhausted you are, until somewhat stands behind you 5 Stars“You do not know how fast you have been running, how hard you have been working, how truly exhausted you are, until somewhat stands behind you and says, “It’s OK, you can fall down now. I’ll catch you.”Whenever I finish a book, I need to learn to sit for a while and think about the book. After finishing a good book, I now realize, I feel so many things, and jumping into writing a  right away will do me no good because I will instantly rate it 5 stars. But, after reading this stunning book, I sat and thought about so many things for a while. This is so dramatic, but I feel like this book has changed me and that I've learned so many lessons from it, that I feel like I will remember for the rest of my life. I learned lessons about love, truth, passion, and power. One of the things I loved about the book was its double narrative. After reading a good story, you usually learn a lesson from it and apply it to your life. Something that the double narrative of the book gave the reader was that reaction after reading a good book. I was able to see how Monique took the lessons she learned from Evelyn's life and applied it to her own, which exemplified the importance of Evelyn's story by showing how it changed Monique's life. It also added some more to the plot and made it more interesting, which is also a bonus. And it also kept you guessing - Why did Evelyn specifically choose Monique to write this story? Where did Monique fall in Evelyn's insane life? (view spoiler)[I was not expecting the end at all. Usually, I feel like I predict some aspect of the end of a book, but this was not something I was excepting and I had not even thought about connecting the dots. (hide spoiler)]I'm not going to sit here and talk about all the lessons I learned from this book because I doubt anyone cares that much, but two of the main things I learned from this book was that just because something doesn't seem entirely perfect, does not mean that it is not good, vice versa. Or in simpler words, not everything is how it seems. To the public, Evelyn may have been seen as someone who couldn't form a connection with someone, I mean with seven husbands? What else could they think? However, it was quite the opposite. Another lesson that I learned was that there are two types of loves - the platonic kind and the romantic kind, and both are equally as amazing and both can make a person just as happy. I learned that maybe some people are only meant to have a romantic, passionate love and some people are only meant to have a platonic, comfortable love, some people both, but at the end of the day, both result in the same things. Happiness. There are so many other lessons in this book, but these definitely stood out to me the most. I think the one things that I may have been slightly disappointed in was the romantic aspect of the book. I feel like Evelyn's relationship with (view spoiler)[ Celia  (hide spoiler)] was a bit underdeveloped and I feel like it was a bit predictable at times, (view spoiler)[ how they would keep leaving each other and then coming back, making their huge arguments seem stupid and meaningless  (hide spoiler)]. However, I still feel like their relationship was so beautiful and the ending made me so happy and sad at the same time. This book also discussed so many important topics about LGBTQ+ people and how especially back in the 1900s, were shunned and how dangerous is was for people to know that you may have been homosexual. And I remember Celia saying something along the lines of, 'how could loving someone be so wrong?' and that just really stuck with me. I could go on and on and talk about all the different aspects of the book, but in conclusion this book was just phenomenal. The writing style of the book was clear cut and easy to read and I hope to read more books like it. I could not put it down and there was not a second that I was bored with it. It is definitely one of my favorites and I highly recommend it....more

then curled up, trembling at every horrific and cruel and selfish thing i’d beheld within that monster - within me. but i had kept watching. i did not turn from it. and when my shaking stopped, i studied it... then i began to see other things. more important things - more vital. ‘and what i saw,’ i said quietly to him as the carver raised a hand. ‘i think - i think i loved it. forgave it - me. all of it’... rhys arched a brow, even as awe swept across his face ‘you loved all of it - the good and the bad?’ i smiled a bit. ‘especially the bad.’- wow. this book was a rollercoaster of freaking emotions - and i loved it. i will say i loved acomaf a bit more but this book was still amazing, so i rounded it up to 5 stars instead of 4. i made some notes while reading the book with my reactions to some things, which will be below this, marked under spoilers, just in case. but overall, i loved the plot of the book. there was so much action, romance, and plot twists that just had me turning review: (1.5 stars) I'm sorry, but I just do not get the hype with this book. Many people claim that this is an addictive book that is hard to put down, but I(1.5 stars) I'm sorry, but I just do not get the hype with this book. Many people claim that this is an addictive book that is hard to put down, but I am going to have to disagree on this one. I will admit that I have DNFed this book many times, so going into it for the third time, determined to read it to the end, my expectations were not very high. First of all, I disliked all the characters. They were all really snobby and the way they reacted to things made me cringe. There were many quotes in the book that just made me cringe and I would have marked them to include in this , but I just didn't even want to waste stickies on them. America was made out to be that one girl that was 'different' from the rest, but I think that whole concept was poorly executed because it just made what happened in the book so much more predictable. Maxon was really whiny and didn't have much character. All the other girls in the book also were really flat characters and I did not care for them much. I also hated the way Cass built the world. Most of it just didn't make any sense. I remember when they were taking a history class and they said something about China invading American for money when America was in debt? If you're going to classify a novel as dystopian, then you might as well create an interesting world that makes sense, and not just base it off the fact that there is a king who holds a 'bachelorette' in his 'palace' every couple of years. And the attacks just bothered me so much, they were so unnecessary and they literally just sat around crying for a whole chapter while it was going on. Like c'mon?! Give me some action here... The book should have gone more into depth with the tensions that they may have with other forces, it would have made the book a little more interesting and the world a little better.Then, we had the crappy romance. (view spoiler)[I thought that the very predictable romance between America and Maxon sucked. (hide spoiler)] While I was reading the book, and not enjoying the story very much, I was hoping that the romance might've compensated for it. I am a sucker for romance, even the smallest amount, but this just sucked. And the whole thing with Aspen was just like, why? Although I found the writing style to be extremely boring, I do think that it was easy to read which was basically the only plus. I didn't have to spend too much time analyzing anything and I could just take it all in and read everything at once. I was never really confused with anything that I was reading and I had no trouble following the story, everything was very clear cut. The only reason I will be continuing to read the series is because someone bought me all the books in the series, so I would feel bad if I didn't, but I also do believe that the story has a bit potential and hopefully the next book will be better. I have read series where the first book sucks, but then eventually the story gets a bit better. The concept of this story was a very good idea, but at the end of the day it was just poorly executed and turned into a predictable and boring read. ...more

It can keep you alive. But don't let it control you. Don't let it sow doubts within you. When the fear takes over, use the only thing more powerful, more indestructible to fight it: your spirit. Your heart.” This book was definitely a rollercoaster, but it didn't really evoke strong emotions in me and it probably won't leave a lasting mark on me. I appreciated the fast-paced plot and all the plot twists, but at the end of the book I wasn't really affected by anything.This book takes place in a very harsh and brutal world. The Masks rule over the Scholars and most Masks are extremely murderous and ruthless people. When I first began to read this, I was shocked at the way the Masks treated the Scholars and I was very intrigued as to why they treated them so horribly. What did the Scholars do to the Masks that made them hate the Scholars so much? We got a short explanation of it towards the end of the book, but I still wanted to learn more. The world-building wasn't too bad, but I've seen better.I'm not sure if I love or hate the way that the dual perspectives worked in this book. Every chapter is switched between Elias' and Laia's point of view. I appreciated the change in plot direction with both and it definitely added to the fast plot, but it made it hard to get invested in both stories. The characters in this book were certainly interesting, but I feel like I didn't really connect to them or know them that well. The Commandment was absolutely horrible and ruthless. She angered me so much, but I am intrigued with her background story and how in the world she came to be the way she is. I feel like I didn't really learn much about Laia or Elias and that their personalities were just based around their 'missions'. I wish I could've seen more of their personalities. I liked Helene and I thought she was interesting. I wish we learned more about her and that she showed up more in the book.The romance in the book was definitely a disappointment. A lot of it felt like instalove and I feel like none of the characters really had any chemistry. review: (3 stars) - Going into this book, I was excited to read it, but did not have high expectations. My friend gave me this book years ago and she let me k(3 stars) - Going into this book, I was excited to read it, but did not have high expectations. My friend gave me this book years ago and she let me keep it because she didn't like the story. I was intrigued by the book and I knew very little going into it. I read some s for it and there was a mix of people who enjoyed it, and people who didn't, and I think I fall in the middle. Something that stuck out to me in this book was the writing. I mostly enjoyed the way this book was written, but sometimes I think all the metaphors were a bit overdone. However, I definitely think it added more to the story and added to that 'summer' atmosphere, which I really loved. I also forgot to mention those little variations on the 'three people' fables and the way they alluded to the story. Before the big revelation, I read the fable and I was like "Wait, wow, I see how this connects to all the Liars," and that really did make me think. The setting of the book had to be one of my favorite aspects about it. I loved the way that the island and all the houses on the island were described. Summer is my favorite season and I feel like summer in particular just gives off certain vibes that I love, where friends are hanging out, staying up late, and doing things they aren't supposed to (view spoiler)[(Not like setting their grandfather's house on fire though haha), (hide spoiler)] and this book does a really good job of giving off that vibe and creating an incredible and beautiful setting.I think the mystery aspect of the book was a bit lacking, which was a big reason this book didn't receive the full five stars. I went into the book hoping that there would be some kind of big revelation at the end of the book, and a big mystery solved, and that did happen, but just not in the way I would've liked. I feel like leading up the revelation, it was super anti-climatic and a bit predictable. I wish I could've gotten more out of it. In no means was it a bad revelation, I just felt like it could've been better, and I was waiting for better.I like most of the Liars and other characters. I won't list them all, but the characters I don't like are for many obvious reasons and if you read the book, you will understand. I had a hard time keeping up with who all the characters were and how Gat came into the picture, but towards the end of the book I understood who everyone was a bit more. I wish the book went into more depth about the individual characters and made them a bit more unique. I think the family dynamic and relationships really added to the story and I enjoyed reading about all those different relationships. I think it was really interesting to read about how privileged this whole family was and how they tried to make it seem like everyone was perfect, even though they were definitely far from it.The romance in the book was very... forgettable. I feel like it just kind of happened and it was super basic. Like I have said in many previous s, I am a sucker for romance and I usually love it in most books, but in this book, nothing really stuck out to me about it, and that's basically all I have to say. Overall, this was not a bad book, it just wasn't an excellent one, hence the three stars rating. I will admit that sometimes I wish that certain parts were a bit more fast-paced, probably because I wanted to know what happened at the end, but I do think the pacing in the book was pretty good. I do recommend this book because I think it is easy to read and a nice mystery. I need to create a psychological thriller shelf for this to put it in, but I would definitely love to read more books of this genre in the future!...more

The gang consists of Kaz, Inej, Nina, Matthias, Jesper, and Wylan. They have to break into the Ice Court, which is nearly impossible to break into, and capture a scientist who created a drug called juda parem. This drug enhances the power of Grisha, a kind of person who has certain abilities and powers. If they ingest it, they become extremely powerful, but fatally addicted to the drug. When I first started the book, I was incredibly confused. Names and places were being thrown at me, and I was just so confused as to what everything was and what it meant. I felt like I was reading a sequel to a book I have never read, and it frustrated me. However, after a couple chapters, I began to understand what everything was and I could easily make distinctions between all the characters.The characters are definitely my favorite part of this book. They are all morally-grey and have interesting back stories. I really enjoyed the dynamic they all had with each other and I really loved the whole gang. review: 4.5 Stars“Men tell stories. Women get on with it. For us it was a shadow war. There were no parades for us when it was over, no medals or mentions in 4.5 Stars“Men tell stories. Women get on with it. For us it was a shadow war. There were no parades for us when it was over, no medals or mentions in history books. We did what we had to during the war, and when it was over, we picked up the pieces and started our lives over.”This book was much different than other WW2 books I have read in the past. It focuses on a different aspect of this war that not many people know about - women's role in the war, specifically in France. Going into the book, I was a bit skeptical. The beginning was slow, illustrating a peaceful life in a small town in France. What could have possibly gone wrong? Suddenly things change and war settles among this town and this book highlights how it impacts the Rossignol sisters, and what their role in the war was. Usually when I read World War 2 books, they are all very similar, but this book stood out. It showed how women played a role in the war, and how it impacted their family, beliefs, and lives. The quote I put above is really important to the story because it shows how women were not recognized properly for all the work they put into the war. This book was raw and it told the truth of what life was like during the war. People died, families were torn apart, extremely unfair things happened, but this book showed how the Rossignol sisters continued to persevere regardless of what happened to protect the things that were most important to them, for Vianne that being her children and for Isabelle that being her beliefs and pride. There were so many times in the novel where I just gasped because I could not believe what was happening and how brave Isabelle and Vianne were being. I found myself connecting a lot to both the characters and I thought all the characters were so well written. The only complaint that I would have with this book is at times I thought it was a bit slow, and I found myself thinking at one point that this would only be a 3.5 star reading but it definitely picked back up again in the last couple hundred pages.The ending was so sad, but incredible and it really hit me. I learned so much from this book and I cannot wait for the movie of this book to be created, I imagine that it will be an incredible and touching movie and that it will get the attention it deserves. Highly recommend!...more

The reason I am giving this 4 stars is that even though I enjoyed this book and finished it all in less than 3 days, it wasn't really anything that blew me away. I didn't really feel connected to the characters, although I definitely enjoyed reading about them. I kind of related to Eliza, but only to a certain point that didn't really allow me to connect with her. I also couldn't really follow along with the Monstrous Sea story. Sometimes parts of it was added to the book, but I honestly had a hard time following it. Maybe that's just me - but it definitely didn't make the book less enjoyable. It just personally, didn't make it more enjoyable for me. Overall, this is a pretty good book and I would definitely recommend it. ...more

review: (4 stars)- this book was beautiful and i'm so grateful that i had the opportunity to read it. it talks about mental health, identity, culture, sexuali(4 stars)- this book was beautiful and i'm so grateful that i had the opportunity to read it. it talks about mental health, identity, culture, sexuality, and so many more important topics. there were so many memorable quotes and chapters for me that i just had to read over and over again. also, i just wanted to put a trigger warning before proceeding with the  because i do talk about sensitive topics, such as suicide.  Memory is a mean thing, slicing at you from the harshest angles, dipping your  consciousness into the wrong colors again and again. A moment of humiliation, or  devastation, or absolute rage, to be rewound and replayed, spinning a thread that  wraps around the brain, knotting itself into something of a noose. It won't exactly  kill you, but it makes you feel the squeeze of every horrible moment. How do you  stop it? How do you work the mind free?this is my first time adding a quote to a , so excuse me if the formatting isn't very good! before i get into the positives, i want to write a little about the negatives and why i didn't give it a full 5 stars, but 4 stars instead. this book was super super slow. i found myself getting a little bored sometimes and it wasn't as fast-paced as i would've liked. another thing is the color analogies. i feel like those were super repetitive and sometimes i found myself felling a bit confused and having to read a part over and over again to try and understand it.on to the positives. the first thing i wanted to talk about was mental health. personally, i have never struggled with any mental illness but it has always been important for me to try and understand mental illnesses. what i loved about this book is that it didn't romanticize depression and the book just described it as it was. (view spoiler)[there wasn't some big revelation to why leigh's mother killed herself. it was simply because she suffered from depression. (hide spoiler)] the book helped me understand that a little more.after reading this book, i couldn't help but go and research the taiwanese culture. taiwan is such a beautiful country and reading about it was one of my favorite things about the book. i loved to hear about all the different foods and traditions, but i especially liked reading about her family history. i found it to be really interesting. another aspect of the book was revealing secrets about dory's family and why they cut off all communications. (view spoiler)[i kind of predicted that feng was dory's sister, jingling, but it still caught me off guard because i didn't actually think that my prediction would be correct. (hide spoiler)] i was eager to find out the reason why dory decided to cut off communication with her parents and it was pretty eye-opening, but it wasn't really a highlight of the book for me. regardless, the culture aspect of the book was one of my favorite parts and i will definitely be researching about taiwan for the next couple of weeks!throughout the book, leigh struggled with her identity. being half-taiwanese and half-american really made it hard for her to figure herself out, especially when in the states she was considered to be 'exotic' and in taiwan she was considered to be 'foreign' and kinda out of place in both countries. i found myself to be relating to it a bit because i am russian, born in america, so sometimes i struggle between figuring out whether i am ukranian or american, thinking that i have to be one or the other. i really appreciated this aspect of the book because of this and i thought it was executed really well. i hope one day i have the opportunity to go back to ukraine and learn more bout my culture and family so that i feel more connected to it.in the book, leigh struggles with her newfound feelings for her bestfriend, axel. many people disliked the romance part of the book, but personally i really enjoyed it. i thought that leigh thinking about axel and her romantic feelings toward him were written really well and i'm glad how it turned out in the end. i think it really interweaved with the whole theme of the book, (view spoiler)[that life goes on and memories are always going to continue to be made. (hide spoiler)] i think axel and leigh were really cute and i love me some good bestfriends to lovers trope!in all, i think that this book was so beautiful and that there were so many layers to the story. this simply isn't a story about suicide and grief, but its about depression, recovering from loss, family, culture, love, and so much more. i highly recommend this book and i definitely will be re-reading it again in the future! ...more
